### Panic in Rust

A panic is an unrecoverable error that causes the program to abort or unwind the stack. It is Rust's mechanism for handling unrecoverable errors.

---

### Panic Behavior

| Build Mode | Behavior |
|------------|----------|
| Debug | Unwinds the stack, prints error message, backtrace |
| Release | Can unwind or abort (configure via Cargo.toml) |

---

### Panic Configuration

```toml
# Cargo.toml - Set panic to abort (no stack unwinding)
[profile.release]
panic = "abort"
```

### When to Panic

```rust
// Examples of appropriate panic usage
fn main() {
    // Array index out of bounds
    let v = vec![1, 2, 3];
    // v[99];  // panics

    // Unwrap when you know it can't fail
    let value = "42".parse::<i32>().unwrap();

    // assert! family (in tests)
    assert!(true);
    assert_eq!(1, 1);
    assert_ne!(1, 2);

    // Explicit panic
    if some_fatal_condition {
        panic!("fatal error: something went wrong");
    }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Panics are for unrecoverable errors and bugs. For recoverable errors, use `Result<T, E>`. Set `panic = "abort"` in release builds for smaller binaries if stack unwinding is not needed.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    println!("Before panic");

    // Uncomment to see panic behavior:
    // panic!("something went wrong!");

    // Array out of bounds panics
    let arr = [1, 2, 3];
    // println!("{}", arr[10]);  // this would panic

    // Catching panic (advanced)
    let result = std::panic::catch_unwind(|| {
        panic!("caught panic");
    });

    match result {
        Ok(_) => println!("Completed"),
        Err(e) => println!("Panic caught: {:?}", e),
    }

    println!("After panic catch");
}
